Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the eurozone was the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 euro-zone countries, inflation was higher than expected in November, with an annual inflation rate of 3.1 per cent after 2.6 per cent in October, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
In contrast to the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the interest rate, which, in its discretion, would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment to create a spiral of inflation.
The ECB strives to keep inflation below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a dilemma: one has to "reciprocate" inflation in order to exclude the need for action at a later stage.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in Germany reached a twelve-year record high in November; in Spain, the rate rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the eurozone was driven by rising food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations increased by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in the price of edible oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but is expected to fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but estimate the annual average rate at 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice.
Gallup Orts Government Crisis
After a long stagnant period, the number of Fidesz sympathizers increased considerably until the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002 the party has the largest base camp, while the approval for the socialists according to Gallup has reached an unprecedented low point of 13 percent.
In the case of party-faith voters, the difference is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: more than two thirds (71 percent) are opposed to one fifth (20 percent) approval for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are under the parliamentary entry hurdle: they reach two percent of the total population.
