Compared to the last low point, the general economic sentiment has deteriorated further - never before has the proportion of those who consider the country's economic situation to be "very bad" been so high (41 percent), while a further 46 percent consider it "quite bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only one tenth assumes a improvement.
A Gallup survey conducted in December revealed that 71% of respondents - a historical high - considered the Prime Minister's work to be "rather bad than right".
Thirteen percent of respondents have great trust or trust in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the proportion of supporters of Viktor Orbán accounts for 38 percent.
