One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of those who think that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister could be managed without a change of government.
After the riots last October, when 35% of the government and the head of government were still in favour of staying, this figure is now only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) see the solution only in new elections.
When asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent replied that they would "participate with certainty" and another 20 percent would "probably" vote.
By way of comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place this Sunday, only 55 per cent would go to the polls "with certainty", while another 15 per cent would consider their participation "probably". In view of these trends, the result of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital daily allowance.
Moved to the group of participants in the referendum "with certainty" the percentage of opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would be 81, 84, or 89 percent.
