In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overburdening of personnel - all factors that are not exactly conducive to containment of infections, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of János Hospital, MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient has been isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection.
The injured person of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with MRSA infection. An important operation could not be performed since then because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient’s body.
By 10 December of this year, the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System reported infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens from hospitals in 1094, according to Karolina Böröcz, head of the National Epidemiology Center.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, but the figure is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of the people in its nose without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually react well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the drugs are given too high or used improperly, the well-responding bacteria produce antibiotic-resistant products that spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
These bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, especially in patients with a weakened immune system, or with a permanently poor immune system, but also in older patients or patients with low body weight.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the everyday life of the sick.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA only does not exist where it is not wanted.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff carries rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment," says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are examined for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of the infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for the control of the formation or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the patients and isolate MRSA infected patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not so common in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the state health insurance fund for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the Epidemiology Center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and disease patterns in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the product, but this directive is not always adhered to by hospitals.
Among the outpatients or patients in primary care, microbiological sampling is even rarer, says Karolina Böröcz.
Disinfectants are saved
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transferred from one patient to the other by the nursing staff.
It is precisely for this reason that hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the local hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
In fact, the rooms are often crowded, the beds lined up close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the less well-off hospitals, it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that almost favour the development of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes the health insurances enormous costs, therefore they are combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government program.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) as well as the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
