Czech Republic has the chance to come to 365 billion
Yesterday, Czech ministers and representatives of the European Commission signed a total of nine development programmes, which will enable the Czech Republic to reach 14 billion euros (about 365 billion kroner) over the next few years.
This is about half the total that the Czech Republic can receive from Brussels in the years 2007 to 2013.
About 125 billion kroner come from seven regional development programmes.
Czech companies will be able to receive around 100 billion kroner from the "Company and Innovation" programme.
The most money, about 150 billion, will flow into the development of transport.
The transport program is the largest development program and comprises up to 22 percent of the funds that the Czech Republic can receive from the fund.
This money will increase in line with the budget of the State Transport Infrastructure Fund, which will have 90.8 billion next year.
The "Enterprise and Innovation" programme is intended to help entrepreneurs and companies to attract funds for innovative ventures.
The aim is for companies to gain finance for the introduction of new technologies, for business research, but also for the introduction of more effective organisational methods.
The Czech Republic is among the least successful among the new candidate countries in the previous EU fund money acquisition.
Nicaraguan Court Confirms Twenty Years of Prison for Ex-Presidents
On Thursday, an appeal court in Nicaragua confirmed the twenty-year prison term for former President Arnold Alemán, to which he was sentenced in 2003 for $100 million (nearly 1.8 billion kroner) in financial fraud.
Later, however, he was released from prison and lived under house arrest on his Hazienda near the Nicaraguan metropolis.
According to the news agency AP, it is currently unclear whether the former head of state (1997 to 2002) of this Central American state will be put behind bars again.
According to Ileana Pérez, the chairman of the Court of Appeals, it will now depend on the prison officials whether Alemán is allowed to serve his sentence at home or whether he has to go to prison.
