He was, after all, an academic who was able to understand and assess technical papers, had experience in statistics and was also an economist.
As the main statement of the book, he described the thesis that the climate is constantly changing and that its changes are therefore normal, that there is no consensus among scientists on global warming, that the consequences of the current changes are not too large and serious and therefore do not pose a threat, and that efforts to influence the development of the climate are superfluous, ineffective and unacceptablely burdensome.
Moreover, as someone with experience of totalitarian systems, he considers it unacceptable to impose unproven views on others, he regards it as a dangerous restriction of freedom.
