Cuba - most beautiful island of the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday will come true if you only choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palm trees and All Inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and beguiling cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean, you will find this in abundant measure.
But only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spaniards, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a camp or transit camp of treasures that the Spaniards had stolen in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20th century.
One of the chiefs of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, had it built, because everything that was considered a crime in the USA (especially during prohibition) was welcomed and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
==References====External links==
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rises grew, and cars crossed the broad boulevards, which were among the cult symbols of the 1950s.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht lying.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
On the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana you can leave your autograph.
At the bar at the Hotel Nacional you can mix cocktails as desired.
And the cult cars of the fifties are still driving around in Havana today, because the once imported Schigulis and Fiats have already fallen apart in the salty and humid air.
Havana, in particular its oldest part, may have been heavily run down, nowhere can you find as many wonderful colonial sights in the vicinity as just here.
Other places are being cleaned out, such as Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, the green light has been given for this development.
In the last fifteen years new hotels have been created not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and also on islets such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a marotte that is unique in the world and especially attracts rail lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam and diesel-powered narrow gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see clean and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have long been in the museum elsewhere.
Excursion destinations
Most of Cuba's visitors do not miss out on the most important places.
So you no longer have to write in detail about Varadero or Havana.
Just to mention that there is a museum in the already mentioned estate of Hemingways, whose visit should not be missed by the one who likes this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on lime soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise up steeply from the bottom of the valley, in their cavities fertile soil accumulated, through which also weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet him when you visit one of Havana's cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
Glory and wealth brought her the trade in slaves and sugar.
The wealth embodied itself in the beautiful beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that in the 1950s there was no road that would have connected the area to the rest of the country.
This isolation helped to keep it unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was torn down, everyone was happy that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon for Trinidad, then it is worth looking at interesting places in the area, such as Playa Ancón beach or the "Valley of Sugar Factorys".
In the evening you should then go to the Casa de la Música, which revives after the darkness, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
Some people call this town the most beautiful of the island in eastern Cuba.
Certainly this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads leading from Guantánamo have to overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape that is hardly touched by human intervention.
UNESCO included this eastern outpost of Cuba in its world heritage directory thanks to the untouched nature there.
There is the best chocolate made, in the church you can see the cross of Columbus (in reality it was created about a hundred years after the journeys of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the current Hotel El Castillo, stands, you can see several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
The coffee, rum, cigars, Sierra Maestra mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, the Tropicana Cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, all this could be written on many sides.
Yes, as they say, look better with your own eyes.
