For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was brought to a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher who had been accused of insulting Islam in Sudan was sentenced to 15 days in prison and subsequent expulsion by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening.
The British woman was accused of allowing six to seven-year-old students to give a teddy bear the name Mahomet, although any representation of the Islamic prophet is prohibited.
She deserved to be flogged.
After having complained several times to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture, the 54-year-old primary school teacher, who worked at the Unity High School in Khartoum, was picked up at home on Sunday and, according to Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code, was accused of insulting Islam.
In fact, this matter begins in September when the teacher asks her six to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy.
The children propose eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed , reports headmaster Robert Boules.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Certainly, Mohammed is the name of the Islamic prophet, but especially a very common first name in Sudan.
Afterwards the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My name is Mohammed .
