A Hard Memory
After being kept confidential for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are located in Bad Arolsen for a total length of 27 km, have not yet been consulted, except with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individual and name-related, i.e. a request from a former victim or his family.
In May 2006, the eleven states responsible for managing them, including Germany, France, Israel and the USA, agreed to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Hot information
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to conduct research, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the state of health of forced laborers, Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which are administered by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public due to the delicate nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or the mental obstruction of some deportation victims.
The inmates' lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest, thus paving the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen still handle tens of thousands of personal inquiries.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
One must not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, explained Pr. Wolfgang Benz, Head of the Research Center for Antisemitism of the Technical University of Berlin, 2006.
The EU and India want a free trade agreement in 2008.
At present, trade between India and Europe is already reaching EUR 60 billion a year.
The EU is India's main trading partner, accounting for 18% of its external trade.
European Trade Minister Peter Mandelson and his Indian counterpart Kamal Nath stated that the European Union and India hope to sign a free trade agreement in 2008.
Last April, EU Foreign Ministers gave the European Commission the green light to open negotiations with a view to signing free trade agreements (ALE) with India, South Korea and the Association of South East Asian Nations (Asean), with trade between India and Europe already reaching 60 billion euros a year.
The EU is India's first trading partner, accounting for 18% of its foreign trade.
The EU is also its first foreign investor, but according to the figures of the European Commission, India is only the EU's ninth trading partner.
A free trade pact will greatly advance the two economic areas and India would improve its access to a market of 450 million wealthy Europeans , confirmed Peter Mandelson.
Europe is the first or second market for the ten products most exported from India, the European Commissioner said. Asian and European giants trade goods worth EUR 47 billion annually and services worth EUR 10 billion, this week Daniéle Smadja, chairman of the European Commission’s delegation in New Delhi, said, and regrets that mutual trade has not yet exhausted its potential. The EU and India will meet on Friday at their eighth diplomatic meeting in New Delhi, where Prime Minister Manmohan Singh and the President of the European Commission José Manuel Durao Barrosso will be present.
