The climate on Venus could give a glimpse of the future of the Earth
The Venus was perhaps once a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spaceship on an orbit show that the planet resembles an averted twin of the Earth even more than it was previously aware of.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to the Earth.
The two worlds are about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, Venus would have had conditions very similar to those on earth and could have been habitable, scientists believe today.
But because of the unabated carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation and a slower rotational pace, Venus took a completely different course of development.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, which examined the planet for one year, offer a sobering view of how the earth could develop in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the heads of the Venus Express Mission, said, "It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar."
"Our new data allows us to construct a scenario in which Venus began billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment."
