Card sharks
Is the credit crisis affecting America's credit card market?
When blood is in the water, it is only natural that back fins swirl around excitedly.
Now that America's real estate market is hurting, predators are targeting the country's credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts expect credit card losses to reach $99 billion if the risk of infection from underfunded loans spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both derecognition and default rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are either not recoverable or more than 30 days late.
Last month, HSBC announced that it had withdrawn a $1.4 billion fee collection from its US consumer financing, partly due to the weakness of credit card holders.
It's still too early to panic.
Losses and delays are still low.
According to Moody, the third quarter default rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in the rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
A change in US private insolvency laws in 2005 led to an abrupt case of bankruptcy applications, which in turn accounted for a large proportion of credit card losses; the number of applications (and hence default fees) would rise again, whether the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate or not.
Industry also reports solid payment rates showing how much of its debt consumers pay off every month
and confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stalemate in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research company, expects that the output volumes for 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
Direct channels of infection between the real estate credit crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: it is more likely that consumers will take credit card debt, now that home loans dry out.
However, card issuers look at the flow of money rather than at capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the borrower's creditworthiness.
They can even be beneficial for card issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue paying mortgage rates fall when real estate is less than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important than repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also react much faster and more flexible than lenders to the stormier conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of assets.
"We won't wake up one day and reassess the loans," says Gary Perlin, Capital One's Chief Financial Officer.
Even if a sudden undercover crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustainable downturn are much more real.
If lower house prices and credit cuts push America into recession, industry will undoubtedly face a more grim future.
