These aren't Warhol's crates
If you connect the terms Sweden and wooden box, think of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, wooden boxes made in Sweden throw dark shadows on Warhol's catalogue of works.
A large part of the ninety-four Brillo boxes of the Stockholm type listed there are forgeries.
After a few months ago, the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes of 1968, internal research in the Moderna Museet in Stockholm is now coming to a sobering conclusion: The six "Brillo boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén gave to the Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - and probably also the majority of the approximately hundred other "Brillo boxes" of the "Sportholm" type, which are in circulation on the international art market.
The prehistory is intertwined, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's consent - exhibited hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these were not from Warhol (for cost reasons) but were delivered directly from the Brillo carton factory.
They were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably gave permission in 1968 to have a few brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, which were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which were then rightly included in the history of art and auctions as authorised original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation "Typ Stockholm".
Some of them have made more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that in 1968 around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were only produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, examined not only the six museum-owned Brillo boxes, but also three from Swedish private property, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press plates were first primed and sanded, and then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press chipboard with a paint roll without primer - in addition, it is not oil paint but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes," says the director of Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve, "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
In July, of course, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "serious accusations" raised in the case of soap powder boxes.
But since then, there has been an inexorable silence.
Rebelling soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebellious soldiers who had entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo have given up.
He could not be responsible for bloodshed, said the leader Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and electoral fraud, reporters at the hotel.
Governmental soldiers had previously stormed the hotel under tear gas.
The approximately two dozen soldiers had been entrenched in the building for hours.
About half of them went to trial on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He used the trial to suddenly settle with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who were supposed to guard him, had apparently defected to him and joined his mutiny.
They invaded the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government troops blocked the district around the noble hotel.
The President called for an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National security adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
"People have enough," Trillanes said.
"We call on people to join us."
General Danilo Lim, who once commanded the Scout Rangers elite unit, said other army units wanted to join the march shortly.
Government critics had called for large demonstrations against the President for Friday.
Their government has been overshadowed by corruption allegations for months.
As early as 2003, Manila's financial district was the main venue for the attempted mutiny of around 200 military personnel against Arroyo.
After almost 24 hours, the uprising failed due to the army's refusal to join.
Since 1986 there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
